        "info": "問題を (mondai o): This part consists of the noun \"問題\" (mondai), meaning \"problem\" or \"issue,\" followed by the particle \"を\" (o). In Japanese, the particle \"を\" (o) marks the direct object of a verb. Here, it indicates that \"問題\" (mondai) is the object of the action.\n\n彼の (kare no): This part consists of the pronoun \"彼\" (kare), meaning \"he,\" and the possessive particle \"の\" (no), which indicates possession. So, \"彼の\" (kare no) means \"his.\"\n\n考えに (kangae ni): This part consists of the noun \"考え\" (kangae), meaning \"thoughts\" or \"ideas,\" followed by the directional particle \"に\" (ni). In Japanese, the particle \"に\" (ni) often indicates direction or destination. Here, it indicates the direction toward which the action is directed.\n\nPutting it all together:\n\n\"問題を\" (mondai o): \"the problem\" (direct object)\n\"彼の\" (kare no): \"his\"\n\"考えに\" (kangae ni): \"thoughts\" (destination)\nSo, \"問題を彼の考えに\" (mondai o kare no kangae ni) translates to \"trouble his thoughts\" or \"affect his thoughts\" in English.",
